## Consensus — The Problem of Agreement

Consensus is the problem of getting a group of processes to agree on a single value, even when some processes crash or messages are delayed. It is provably impossible in a fully asynchronous system with even one faulty node (FLP impossibility, 1985). Real systems work around this with timeouts.

### Why Paxos Is Not Used Directly

Paxos (Lamport, 1989) solves consensus but is famously hard to implement correctly. Raft (Ongaro & Ousterhout, 2014) was designed to be **understandable** — same guarantees, clearer decomposition.

## Raft in Detail

Raft decomposes consensus into three sub-problems:

1. **Leader election** — choose one authoritative node
2. **Log replication** — leader appends, followers copy
3. **Safety** — no two leaders in the same term, committed entries never lost

### Leader Election

Every node starts as a **Follower**. If it receives no heartbeat within its **election timeout** (randomised 150–300 ms), it becomes a **Candidate** and requests votes.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Follower
    Follower --> Candidate: election timeout fires
    Candidate --> Leader: receives majority votes
    Candidate --> Follower: discovers higher term
    Leader --> Follower: discovers higher term
    Leader --> Leader: sends heartbeats every 50ms
```

**Vote granting rules**:
- A node votes for a candidate only if the candidate's log is at least as up-to-date as its own
- A node votes for at most one candidate per term
- A candidate needs votes from floor(n/2) + 1 nodes (majority)

```python
from dataclasses import dataclass, field
from typing import Optional
import random

@dataclass
class RaftNode:
    node_id: str
    peers: list
    current_term: int = 0
    voted_for: Optional[str] = None
    state: str = "follower"
    log: list = field(default_factory=list)
    votes_received: set = field(default_factory=set)
    election_timeout: float = field(
        default_factory=lambda: random.uniform(0.15, 0.30)
    )

    def start_election(self) -> dict:
        self.current_term += 1
        self.state = "candidate"
        self.voted_for = self.node_id
        self.votes_received = {self.node_id}
        last_log_index = len(self.log) - 1
        last_log_term = self.log[-1]["term"] if self.log else 0
        return {
            "type": "RequestVote",
            "term": self.current_term,
            "candidate_id": self.node_id,
            "last_log_index": last_log_index,
            "last_log_term": last_log_term,
        }

    def handle_vote_response(self, granted: bool, from_node: str):
        if granted:
            self.votes_received.add(from_node)
        majority = len(self.peers) // 2 + 1
        if len(self.votes_received) >= majority:
            self.state = "leader"
            print(f"Node {self.node_id} elected leader for term {self.current_term}")
            print(f"Votes: {self.votes_received} (needed {majority} of {len(self.peers)+1})")

node = RaftNode("A", peers=["B", "C", "D", "E"])
vote_req = node.start_election()
print(f"Election started: term={vote_req['term']}")
node.handle_vote_response(True, "B")
node.handle_vote_response(True, "C")  # now has 3/5 — majority
```

### Log Replication

Once elected, the leader accepts client writes and replicates them:

```typescript
interface LogEntry {
  term: number;
  index: number;
  command: string;
}

class RaftLeader {
  private log: LogEntry[] = [];
  private commitIndex = 0;
  private matchIndex: Map<string, number>;
  private currentTerm: number;
  private followers: string[];

  constructor(followers: string[], term: number) {
    this.followers = followers;
    this.currentTerm = term;
    this.matchIndex = new Map(followers.map(f => [f, -1]));
  }

  appendEntry(command: string): number {
    const entry: LogEntry = {
      term: this.currentTerm,
      index: this.log.length,
      command,
    };
    this.log.push(entry);
    console.log(`Entry at index=${entry.index} pending commit (need majority ACK)`);
    return entry.index;
  }

  onFollowerACK(followerId: string, matchIndex: number): boolean {
    this.matchIndex.set(followerId, matchIndex);
    const replicated = [...this.matchIndex.values()].filter(i => i >= matchIndex).length;
    const majority = Math.floor((this.followers.length + 1) / 2) + 1;
    if (replicated >= majority - 1) {
      this.commitIndex = matchIndex;
      console.log(`Committed index=${matchIndex}`);
      return true;
    }
    return false;
  }
}
```

### Safety Guarantee

Raft guarantees: if two logs contain an entry with the same index and term, the logs are **identical** in all entries up through that index. A new leader can only be elected if it has **all committed entries**.

### Practical Numbers

| Parameter | Typical Value | Effect |
|-----------|--------------|--------|
| Election timeout | 150–300 ms (randomised) | Prevents simultaneous elections |
| Heartbeat interval | 50 ms | Must be << election timeout |
| Leader election time | 150–300 ms | Recovery speed after leader failure |
| etcd throughput (3-node DC) | ~10,000 writes/sec | p99 < 1 ms |

## Split-Brain and How Raft Prevents It

In Raft, split-brain cannot happen in the same term because a node can only vote once per term and two majorities cannot exist simultaneously in a cluster of n nodes.

```mermaid
graph LR
    subgraph "5-node cluster — network partition"
        subgraph "Partition A (3 nodes)"
            A["Node A — Leader term 5"]
            B["Node B — Follower"]
            C["Node C — Follower"]
        end
        subgraph "Partition B (2 nodes)"
            D["Node D — Candidate (cannot get majority)"]
            E["Node E — Follower"]
        end
    end
    style A fill:#27ae60,color:#fff
    style D fill:#e74c3c,color:#fff
```

## Interview Q&A

**Q: How long does Raft leader election take?**
A: Typically one election timeout interval: 150–300 ms. With randomised timeouts, the probability of a split vote requiring multiple rounds is low (< 10% in practice).

**Q: What happens to writes during leader election?**
A: They are rejected (the cluster is unavailable for writes for the election duration). This is the CP choice.

**Q: What is a "term" in Raft?**
A: A monotonically increasing logical clock. Each election attempt starts a new term. Terms are used to detect stale leaders — if a node receives a message with a higher term, it immediately reverts to follower.

